               <p>956. <persName id="def1-956-18410301" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-956-18410301" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-956-18410301" type="surname" value="JOHNSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-956-18410301" type="given" value="NICHOLAS"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">NICHOLAS JOHNSON</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18410301-956-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18410301-956-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18410301-956-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="embezzlement"></interp>for embezzlement.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BOANE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18410301-name-920" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18410301-name-920" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410301-name-920" type="surname" value="PEARCE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410301-name-920" type="given" value="ROBERT WILLIAM"></interp>ROBERT WILLIAM PEARCE</persName>
                  </hi>. My wife is a milliner and lives in Regent-street—the prisoner was her errand<lb></lb>boy—it was his business to take out goods, to receive money, and to account to nay wife or to Miss Hensball—I discharged him on the 14th of February—after he was gone, I found</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184103010162"></xptr>
               <p>him in Charles-street, Middlesex Hospital—I said, "I suppose you know me?"—he said, "Yes"—I said, "I am come respecting Mrs. Redman's money"—his countenance changed, and he said, "I have not received it"—I said, "You have—I have sent to that lady, her servant paid you, and has your receipt, which she can produce"—he denied it, and I gave him into custody.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You discharged him, but not for any fault? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He had many faults, but I was not aware of this—my wife is not here—the prisoner did not say, that if he bad received this, he had accounted for it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18410301-name-921" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18410301-name-921" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410301-name-921" type="surname" value="HENSHALL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410301-name-921" type="given" value="ELIZA"></interp>ELIZA HENSHALL</persName>
                  </hi>. I am forewoman to Mrs. Pearce, of Regent-street On the 5th of February, I sent the prisoner with a cap to Mrs. Redman—it was his duty to receive the money and to account to me on his return—I particularly told him there was a bill in it, and a receipt to it, and that he was to wait—he went with it—the next day was Saturday—I was not well, and was not there—I saw him on the Monday morning, and asked him for the money—he said she had not paid him, as she had a party there, or was going to a party and did not pay him—I asked him if he had taken the receipt off the bill, he said he had, and had got it somewhere—he attempted to look for it, but did not produce it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did you put the receipt in the box? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; the young person who makes out the bills told me it was there.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18410301-name-922" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18410301-name-922" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410301-name-922" type="surname" value="MANNING"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410301-name-922" type="given" value="ELIZA EMMA"></interp>ELIZA EMMA MANNING</persName>
                  </hi>. I am housemaid to Mrs. Redman, of Canton-place, Limehouse. On the 5th of February the prisoner came, and brought a cap in a box—I took it to my mistress, and when it was opened I saw the bill in it—no part of it was torn off—my mistress gave me 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., which I paid to the prisoner—this is the bill and receipt.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> What time was this? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> A little after seven o'clock on Friday evening.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18410301-name-923" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18410301-name-923" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410301-name-923" type="surname" value="WYNESS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18410301-name-923" type="given" value="ANDREW"></interp>ANDREW WYNESS</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable D</hi> 43.) I went to the lodging with Mr. Pearce, and saw the prisoner—he said he had not had the money—I put my hand on his arm—he squared up to me, and said he would knock my head about.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18410301-956-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
